<name><![CDATA[Charles' Law]]></name>
<background><![CDATA[Charles' Law states that under conditions of constant pressure and quantity, there is a direct relationship between the volume and absolute temperature for an ideal gas. 

The mathematical statement is that the <i>V/T</i>= a constant. For two sets of conditions the following is a math statement of Charles's Law:

<i>V<sub>1</sub>/T<sub>1</sub> = V<sub>2</sub>/T<sub>2</sub></i>

In this experiment you will vary the temperature of a sample of gas and measure the change in volume to study this relationship. Having the Gas Syringe makes your work easier because the gas inside is always at atmospheric pressure.
]]></background>
<assignment><![CDATA[<b>Assignment 1 of Procedure 1</b>

1. Prepare a graph of the data for methane with temperature (in Kelvin) on the X-axis and volume (mL) on the Y-axis.

2. Draw a straight line through the data points.

3. Does your experimental data verify Charles' Law? 

4. What volume would the gas sample occupy at 50°C, and at 120°C?

5. List two sources of possible error if you had done the activity in a real lab.

<b>Procedure 2</b>

1. Prepare a graph of the data for butane with temperature (in Kelvin) on the X-axis and volume (mL) on the Y-axis.

2. Draw a straight line through the data points.

3. Does your experimental data verify Charles' Law?

4. What volume would the gas sample occupy at 0°C, and at 70°C?

5. List two sources of possible error if you had done the activity in a real lab. 
]]></assignment>
<procedure><![CDATA[<b>Procedure #1</b>

Butane and methane are combustible materials that can explode if ignited. In this vitual investigation, assume that all experimental work occurs within a fume hood in which there are no open flames.

1. Take a gas syringe from the Glassware shelf and place it on the workbench.

2. Fill the gas syringe with 100 mL of methane gas (CH<sub>4</sub>) from the Chemicals shelf. 

3. Open the Data window, and click on the gas syringe to view the volume of the gas sample.

4. Take a thermometer from the Tools shelf and drag it to the gas syringe to connect them. Double click on the thermometer, and set the temperature units to "K".

5. Record the temperature (in Kelvin) and the volume of the gas sample.

6. Take a Constant Temperature Bath from the Tools shelf and place it on the workbench. 

7. Use the arrows on the front of the bath to adjust the bath setting to "ice".

8. Drag the gas syringe and drop it on the constant temperature bath.

9. Let the temperature of the gas sample stabilize; then record the temperature and volume of the gas sample.

10. Adjust the temperature of the bath to 40°C and record the temperature and volume of the gas once it stabilizes. Click on the syringe to refresh the Data Window and see information.

11. Repeat the measurements for bath settings of 60°C, 80°C and 100°C.

<b>Procedure #2</b>

Optional: Repeat the steps of Procedure 1 for butane gas (C<sub>4</sub>H<sub>10</sub>). 

Note: The boiling point of butane gas is just below 0°C, so, skip the step of setting the bath to "ice".
]]></procedure>
